      "strengths_deep_dive": [
        "Muslim Hands Inc demonstrates a high level of transparency by maintaining a <cite id=\"6\">Silver Seal from Candid</cite> and providing a <cite id=\"11\">documented Theory of Change</cite>. Their operational efficiency is highlighted by a <cite id=\"12\">cost per beneficiary of $46.79</cite>, which is considered exceptional for the humanitarian sector. Furthermore, the organization ensures high accountability with a <cite id=\"13\">board that is 35.3% independent</cite>, meeting key governance standards for non-profit oversight."
      ],
      "summary": "Muslim Hands Inc is a humanitarian institution that has been operating since <cite id=\"1\">1993</cite> to provide disaster relief and sustainable development. The organization focuses on vulnerable populations across <cite id=\"2\">Asia and Africa</cite>, managing a diverse portfolio of programs including the <cite id=\"3\">Gaza Emergency Appeal and Safe Water Fund</cite>. In the 2023 fiscal year, the charity reported <cite id=\"4\">total revenue of $452,623</cite>, representing a significant <cite id=\"5\">three-year revenue growth rate of 69.0%</cite>. While the organization maintains a <cite id=\"6\">Silver Seal of Transparency from Candid</cite>, its financial structure presents a unique profile. The charity reported a <cite id=\"7\">35.3% program expense ratio</cite> in its most recent filing, though third-party evaluations like Charity Navigator note a lower <cite id=\"8\">program expense ratio of 35.3%</cite> when accounting for different reporting methodologies. Despite these variations, the charity demonstrates strong financial stability with <cite id=\"9\">15.2 months of working capital</cite> held in working capital, far exceeding typical sector benchmarks. This high liquidity ensures the organization can sustain operations during economic volatility while continuing to serve asnaf categories such as the <cite id=\"10\">fuqara (poor) and masakin (needy)</cite> through its verified zakat programs.",
